Reasoning: The paper deals with algorithms for matching problems in graphs, which falls under the category of data structures (cs.DS) and graph theory (cs.GT). The use of randomized algorithms and analysis of their performance suggests that the paper may also belong to the information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Finally, the study of lower bounds and complexity of the problem may also place the paper in the computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. However, since the focus is primarily on algorithms and graph theory, we consider cs.NE (networks and networking) to be less likely.
